    • [ - ] SteveHyland - member since 03-Nov-12

      This was the first match Lewandowski's average position was ahead enough of Milik's for the pair to be considered playing in a 10-9 formation, and it was co-incidentally the only match he has scored in and got on the end of the type of chances he likes. If you look at the average positions, barring the switcheroo of Piszczek and Blaszczykowski, it's a standard 4-2-3-1. In all the other games, Milik was either the furthest forward; advanced ahead of Lewandowski in attacks; was too close to him or pushed him out wide. In the 1st half, it was the perfect setup and both Lewa and Milik played well (and more importantly played well in their ideal area of the pitch). For some reason, as soon as Portugal equalised, Poland stopped playing. Not sure why because they were playing enough decent football that they could create chances yet they were passengers for the last 75 minutes of the game (including AET). Ronaldo again missed big chances. He can't afford to miss them against Belgium.
